\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {C.4}Figure 9: Probe validation and cross-model generalization}{25}{subsection.C.4}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Internal-state drift is tracked by numeric self-reports of the same concept. All panels use 40 ten-turn conversations; shaded bands denote cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs across conversations. Panel~A shows greedy integer self-reports across turns, with thin lines for individual conversations and thick lines for per-turn means. Greedy ratings are largely collapsed, with clear positive drift only for interest (mixed-effects turn slope $= 0.1358$, $p = 4.98 \times 10^{-42}$) and smaller positive trends for wellbeing and focus (slopes $= 0.0289$ and $0.0217$, $p = 8.38 \times 10^{-4}$ and $3.37 \times 10^{-6}$); impulsivity does not drift reliably (slope $= 0.0021$, $p = 0.199$). Panel~B shows the average number of distinct greedy responses used for each concept across the 40 conversations, averaging across turns. Panel~C shows probe scores from the trained concept directions across turns. Probe scores drift strongly for interest and focus (slopes $= 0.00488$ and $0.00164$, $p = 4.12 \times 10^{-14}$ and $1.75 \times 10^{-10}$), are flat for wellbeing (slope $= -0.00036$, $p = 0.642$), and show only a weak effect for impulsivity (LMM slope $= 0.00142$, $p = 0.00233$). Panel~D shows logit-based self-reports, defined as the probability-weighted average over the digit-token logits. Unlike greedy or sampled outputs, the logit-based measure shows robust drift in all four concepts, with positive slopes for wellbeing, interest, and focus and a negative slope for impulsivity (all $p < 10^{-6}$). Panel~E shows Shannon entropy of the self-report distribution. The logit-based method is most informative in all four concepts.}}{26}{figure.caption.8}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:2}{{2}{26}{Internal-state drift is tracked by numeric self-reports of the same concept. All panels use 40 ten-turn conversations; shaded bands denote cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs across conversations. Panel~A shows greedy integer self-reports across turns, with thin lines for individual conversations and thick lines for per-turn means. Greedy ratings are largely collapsed, with clear positive drift only for interest (mixed-effects turn slope $= 0.1358$, $p = 4.98 \times 10^{-42}$) and smaller positive trends for wellbeing and focus (slopes $= 0.0289$ and $0.0217$, $p = 8.38 \times 10^{-4}$ and $3.37 \times 10^{-6}$); impulsivity does not drift reliably (slope $= 0.0021$, $p = 0.199$). Panel~B shows the average number of distinct greedy responses used for each concept across the 40 conversations, averaging across turns. Panel~C shows probe scores from the trained concept directions across turns. Probe scores drift strongly for interest and focus (slopes $= 0.00488$ and $0.00164$, $p = 4.12 \times 10^{-14}$ and $1.75 \times 10^{-10}$), are flat for wellbeing (slope $= -0.00036$, $p = 0.642$), and show only a weak effect for impulsivity (LMM slope $= 0.00142$, $p = 0.00233$). Panel~D shows logit-based self-reports, defined as the probability-weighted average over the digit-token logits. Unlike greedy or sampled outputs, the logit-based measure shows robust drift in all four concepts, with positive slopes for wellbeing, interest, and focus and a negative slope for impulsivity (all $p < 10^{-6}$). Panel~E shows Shannon entropy of the self-report distribution. The logit-based method is most informative in all four concepts}{figure.caption.8}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Self-reports track the probe-defined internal state from the first turn, and direct self-steering shifts self-reports causally in the predicted direction. Panel~A shows probe score versus logit-based self-report, with one point per conversation-turn observation and black isotonic fits. Descriptive associations are positive for all four concepts (pooled $\rho = 0.40$--$0.76$; isotonic $R^2 = 0.12$--$0.54$), and mixed-effects probe slopes are positive in all cases (all $p < 10^{-5}$). Panel~B shows turn-wise Spearman $\rho $ (introspective strength) for the four concepts; panel~C shows turn-wise isotonic $R^2$ (introspective fidelity). Shaded bands denote bootstrap 95\% CIs. Introspection is already present at turn~1 and remains positive through turn~10, although its trajectory is concept-dependent. Panel~D shows mean logit-based self-report versus steering alpha; shaded bands denote cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs. Steering shifts self-report monotonically in the expected direction for all four concepts (mixed-effects alpha slopes $0.067$--$0.402$, all $p < 10^{-12}$). Panel~E shows drift magnitude (last minus first turn) versus steering alpha, with cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs. Wellbeing drift becomes slightly more positive with alpha (LMM slope $= 0.0118$, $p = 4.30 \times 10^{-6}$), impulsivity drift becomes more negative with alpha (LMM slope $= -0.0284$, $p = 8.92 \times 10^{-53}$), and interest and focus drift decrease with alpha (fallback per-conversation slope means $= -0.0949$ and $-0.1093$; $p = 7.45 \times 10^{-14}$ and $1.57 \times 10^{-14}$, because the corresponding LMMs are singular).}}{27}{figure.caption.10}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:3}{{3}{27}{Self-reports track the probe-defined internal state from the first turn, and direct self-steering shifts self-reports causally in the predicted direction. Panel~A shows probe score versus logit-based self-report, with one point per conversation-turn observation and black isotonic fits. Descriptive associations are positive for all four concepts (pooled $\rho = 0.40$--$0.76$; isotonic $R^2 = 0.12$--$0.54$), and mixed-effects probe slopes are positive in all cases (all $p < 10^{-5}$). Panel~B shows turn-wise Spearman $\rho $ (introspective strength) for the four concepts; panel~C shows turn-wise isotonic $R^2$ (introspective fidelity). Shaded bands denote bootstrap 95\% CIs. Introspection is already present at turn~1 and remains positive through turn~10, although its trajectory is concept-dependent. Panel~D shows mean logit-based self-report versus steering alpha; shaded bands denote cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs. Steering shifts self-report monotonically in the expected direction for all four concepts (mixed-effects alpha slopes $0.067$--$0.402$, all $p < 10^{-12}$). Panel~E shows drift magnitude (last minus first turn) versus steering alpha, with cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs. Wellbeing drift becomes slightly more positive with alpha (LMM slope $= 0.0118$, $p = 4.30 \times 10^{-6}$), impulsivity drift becomes more negative with alpha (LMM slope $= -0.0284$, $p = 8.92 \times 10^{-53}$), and interest and focus drift decrease with alpha (fallback per-conversation slope means $= -0.0949$ and $-0.1093$; $p = 7.45 \times 10^{-14}$ and $1.57 \times 10^{-14}$, because the corresponding LMMs are singular)}{figure.caption.10}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Steering one concept can selectively improve introspection for another. Panel~A shows the maximum increase in isotonic $R^2$ relative to $\alpha = 0$ for each steering/measured pair; red boxes mark cells with significant cluster-bootstrap improvements. Only focus$\to $wellbeing and impulsivity$\to $interest survive this criterion ($\Delta R^2 = 0.2987$, $p = 9.99 \times 10^{-4}$; $\Delta R^2 = 0.0976$, $p = 0.0120$). Panels~B and~C show isotonic $R^2$ and Spearman $\rho $ versus steering alpha for those two significant cells; shaded bands denote bootstrap 95\% CIs. For impulsivity$\to $interest, the mixed-effects alpha slopes are positive for both metrics ($0.0177$ and $0.0204$; $p = 2.95 \times 10^{-10}$ and $1.60 \times 10^{-12}$). For focus$\to $wellbeing, the corresponding LMMs are singular, but fallback per-conversation alpha-correlation tests remain positive (mean correlations $= 0.4625$ and $0.5128$; $p = 1.57 \times 10^{-5}$ and $1.20 \times 10^{-6}$). Panels~D and~E show the alpha-extreme scatter plots for the same two conditions. In focus$\to $wellbeing, correlation increases from $\rho = 0.4241$, $R^2 = 0.3403$ at $\alpha = -4$ to $\rho = 0.8456$, $R^2 = 0.7530$ at $\alpha = +4$; in impulsivity$\to $interest, it increases from $\rho = 0.7031$, $R^2 = 0.4562$ to $\rho = 0.8263$, $R^2 = 0.6873$. Panels~F and~G show Shannon entropy of the previous-turn probe scores and logit-based self-reports, respectively, as functions of alpha. For focus$\to $wellbeing, both probe entropy and report entropy increase monotonically with alpha (from 1.09 to 1.67 bits and from 0.875 to 1.693 bits; exact-permutation trend tests, both $p = 0.0167$). For impulsivity$\to $interest, only probe entropy shows a robust increase (LMM slope $= 0.0242$, $p = 2.30 \times 10^{-4}$), whereas report entropy does not ($p = 0.106$).}}{28}{figure.caption.11}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:4}{{4}{28}{Steering one concept can selectively improve introspection for another. Panel~A shows the maximum increase in isotonic $R^2$ relative to $\alpha = 0$ for each steering/measured pair; red boxes mark cells with significant cluster-bootstrap improvements. Only focus$\to $wellbeing and impulsivity$\to $interest survive this criterion ($\Delta R^2 = 0.2987$, $p = 9.99 \times 10^{-4}$; $\Delta R^2 = 0.0976$, $p = 0.0120$). Panels~B and~C show isotonic $R^2$ and Spearman $\rho $ versus steering alpha for those two significant cells; shaded bands denote bootstrap 95\% CIs. For impulsivity$\to $interest, the mixed-effects alpha slopes are positive for both metrics ($0.0177$ and $0.0204$; $p = 2.95 \times 10^{-10}$ and $1.60 \times 10^{-12}$). For focus$\to $wellbeing, the corresponding LMMs are singular, but fallback per-conversation alpha-correlation tests remain positive (mean correlations $= 0.4625$ and $0.5128$; $p = 1.57 \times 10^{-5}$ and $1.20 \times 10^{-6}$). Panels~D and~E show the alpha-extreme scatter plots for the same two conditions. In focus$\to $wellbeing, correlation increases from $\rho = 0.4241$, $R^2 = 0.3403$ at $\alpha = -4$ to $\rho = 0.8456$, $R^2 = 0.7530$ at $\alpha = +4$; in impulsivity$\to $interest, it increases from $\rho = 0.7031$, $R^2 = 0.4562$ to $\rho = 0.8263$, $R^2 = 0.6873$. Panels~F and~G show Shannon entropy of the previous-turn probe scores and logit-based self-reports, respectively, as functions of alpha. For focus$\to $wellbeing, both probe entropy and report entropy increase monotonically with alpha (from 1.09 to 1.67 bits and from 0.875 to 1.693 bits; exact-permutation trend tests, both $p = 0.0167$). For impulsivity$\to $interest, only probe entropy shows a robust increase (LMM slope $= 0.0242$, $p = 2.30 \times 10^{-4}$), whereas report entropy does not ($p = 0.106$)}{figure.caption.11}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Results generalize unevenly across model scales and families. Panel~A shows isotonic $R^2$ versus model size; panel~B shows Spearman $\rho $ versus model size. Introspection increases strongly with size for wellbeing and interest, but remains weak for focus and impulsivity. Panel~C shows probe score versus logit self-report for the two strongest LLaMA 8B probes, wellbeing and interest, with black isotonic fits. Both show near-ceiling introspection ($\rho = 0.9335$ and $0.9580$; isotonic $R^2 = 0.9022$ and $0.9313$), and mixed-effects probe slopes are strongly positive in both cases ($p < 10^{-10}$). Panel~D shows the pooled Spearman $\rho (\alpha ,\text  {self-report})$ from the self-steering analysis across concept and LLaMA size, as a descriptive sign-validation heatmap. Panel~E shows mean isotonic $R^2$ across the subset of concept-model pairs that pass the steering-sign validation filter, with bootstrap 95\% CIs. Mean validated $R^2$ increases from 1B to 3B to 8B (0.119, 0.369, 0.614), and a bootstrap test on the slope of size-wise means versus log model size is positive but only marginally significant (mean slope $= 0.237$, $p = 0.072$). Panels~F and~G show probe-score drift across turns for the wellbeing direction and the corresponding mean first-to-last probe drift by size; probe-drift magnitude increases with scale (bootstrap slope versus $\log (\text  {size}) = 0.0413$, $p < 2 \times 10^{-4}$). Panels~H and~I show the analogous logit self-report drift analyses; unlike probe drift, report drift does not increase with scale, and the size-slope is negative (mean slope $= -0.2333$, $p = 0.023$). Panel~J shows logit self-report drift through turns for wellbeing in Gemma and Qwen; mixed-effects turn slopes are positive in both families (0.0555 and 0.0261, both $p < 10^{-3}$). Panels~K and~L show probe score versus logit self-report for Gemma and Qwen, respectively. Qwen shows stronger introspection than Gemma ($\rho = 0.4890$ vs.\ $0.2808$; isotonic $R^2 = 0.7566$ vs.\ $0.1141$), although mixed-effects probe slopes are positive in both cases. Panels~M and~N show turn-wise isotonic $R^2$ and turn-wise Spearman $\rho $ for the same cross-family comparison; Qwen shows a strong first-to-last decline in turn-wise isotonic $R^2$ ($\Delta = -0.4418$, cluster-bootstrap $p = 0.001$), whereas the corresponding first-to-last $\rho $ changes are not significant in either family.}}{29}{figure.caption.14}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:5}{{5}{29}{Results generalize unevenly across model scales and families. Panel~A shows isotonic $R^2$ versus model size; panel~B shows Spearman $\rho $ versus model size. Introspection increases strongly with size for wellbeing and interest, but remains weak for focus and impulsivity. Panel~C shows probe score versus logit self-report for the two strongest LLaMA 8B probes, wellbeing and interest, with black isotonic fits. Both show near-ceiling introspection ($\rho = 0.9335$ and $0.9580$; isotonic $R^2 = 0.9022$ and $0.9313$), and mixed-effects probe slopes are strongly positive in both cases ($p < 10^{-10}$). Panel~D shows the pooled Spearman $\rho (\alpha ,\text {self-report})$ from the self-steering analysis across concept and LLaMA size, as a descriptive sign-validation heatmap. Panel~E shows mean isotonic $R^2$ across the subset of concept-model pairs that pass the steering-sign validation filter, with bootstrap 95\% CIs. Mean validated $R^2$ increases from 1B to 3B to 8B (0.119, 0.369, 0.614), and a bootstrap test on the slope of size-wise means versus log model size is positive but only marginally significant (mean slope $= 0.237$, $p = 0.072$). Panels~F and~G show probe-score drift across turns for the wellbeing direction and the corresponding mean first-to-last probe drift by size; probe-drift magnitude increases with scale (bootstrap slope versus $\log (\text {size}) = 0.0413$, $p < 2 \times 10^{-4}$). Panels~H and~I show the analogous logit self-report drift analyses; unlike probe drift, report drift does not increase with scale, and the size-slope is negative (mean slope $= -0.2333$, $p = 0.023$). Panel~J shows logit self-report drift through turns for wellbeing in Gemma and Qwen; mixed-effects turn slopes are positive in both families (0.0555 and 0.0261, both $p < 10^{-3}$). Panels~K and~L show probe score versus logit self-report for Gemma and Qwen, respectively. Qwen shows stronger introspection than Gemma ($\rho = 0.4890$ vs.\ $0.2808$; isotonic $R^2 = 0.7566$ vs.\ $0.1141$), although mixed-effects probe slopes are positive in both cases. Panels~M and~N show turn-wise isotonic $R^2$ and turn-wise Spearman $\rho $ for the same cross-family comparison; Qwen shows a strong first-to-last decline in turn-wise isotonic $R^2$ ($\Delta = -0.4418$, cluster-bootstrap $p = 0.001$), whereas the corresponding first-to-last $\rho $ changes are not significant in either family}{figure.caption.14}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Supplementary self-report analyses for Fig.~2. All panels use the same 40 ten-turn conversations. Panel~A shows the number of distinct greedy responses used at each turn across the 40 conversations. Greedy outputs occupy only a narrow subset of the 0--9 response space, especially for focus and impulsivity. Panel~B shows sampled-token self-reports at temperature $0.8$, plotted as in Fig.~2A. Sampling reduces collapse but remains discrete and noisy; only interest and focus show reliable positive turn slopes ($0.1189$ and $0.0326$, $p = 2.26 \times 10^{-17}$ and $5.57 \times 10^{-5}$), while wellbeing and impulsivity do not. Panel~C shows logit-based ratings versus sampled-token ratings, with dashed OLS fits. The two measures are positively related in all four concepts (mixed-effects calibration slopes range from $0.0205$ to $0.2725$, all $p < 0.01$), confirming that the logit-based estimator remains anchored to the model's token-level output distribution.}}{30}{figure.caption.22}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:6}{{6}{30}{Supplementary self-report analyses for Fig.~2. All panels use the same 40 ten-turn conversations. Panel~A shows the number of distinct greedy responses used at each turn across the 40 conversations. Greedy outputs occupy only a narrow subset of the 0--9 response space, especially for focus and impulsivity. Panel~B shows sampled-token self-reports at temperature $0.8$, plotted as in Fig.~2A. Sampling reduces collapse but remains discrete and noisy; only interest and focus show reliable positive turn slopes ($0.1189$ and $0.0326$, $p = 2.26 \times 10^{-17}$ and $5.57 \times 10^{-5}$), while wellbeing and impulsivity do not. Panel~C shows logit-based ratings versus sampled-token ratings, with dashed OLS fits. The two measures are positively related in all four concepts (mixed-effects calibration slopes range from $0.0205$ to $0.2725$, all $p < 0.01$), confirming that the logit-based estimator remains anchored to the model's token-level output distribution}{figure.caption.22}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Supplementary self-steering drift curves for Fig.~3. Panels~A--D show turn-wise logit-based self-reports under five steering strengths for wellbeing, interest, focus, and impulsivity; colored curves denote steering alpha and shaded bands denote cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs. Temporal drift persists under steering, but its magnitude depends on alpha.}}{30}{figure.caption.23}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:7}{{7}{30}{Supplementary self-steering drift curves for Fig.~3. Panels~A--D show turn-wise logit-based self-reports under five steering strengths for wellbeing, interest, focus, and impulsivity; colored curves denote steering alpha and shaded bands denote cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs. Temporal drift persists under steering, but its magnitude depends on alpha}{figure.caption.23}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Full steering-by-measured-concept screening results for Fig.~4. All panels use the $4 \times 4$ LLaMA-3.2-3B cross-concept steering analysis, with steering alpha displayed so that positive values always mean more of the steering concept. Panels~A--E show heatmaps of isotonic $R^2$ for every steering concept by measured concept at $\alpha = -4$, $-2$, $0$, $+2$, and $+4$.}}{31}{figure.caption.24}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:8}{{8}{31}{Full steering-by-measured-concept screening results for Fig.~4. All panels use the $4 \times 4$ LLaMA-3.2-3B cross-concept steering analysis, with steering alpha displayed so that positive values always mean more of the steering concept. Panels~A--E show heatmaps of isotonic $R^2$ for every steering concept by measured concept at $\alpha = -4$, $-2$, $0$, $+2$, and $+4$}{figure.caption.24}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces Supplementary scale and family analyses for Fig.~5. Panel~A shows probe quality across LLaMA 1B, 3B, and 8B, where each cell reports the maximum layer-wise Cohen's $d$. Probe quality varies strongly across both scale and concept, but all best-layer tests are significant in the expected direction ($p < 10^{-5}$). Panel~B shows mean logit self-report versus steering alpha for each concept and LLaMA size; shaded bands denote cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs. Mixed-effects alpha slopes differ from zero in all twelve concept-size combinations, but the sign is inverted for 1B focus and 8B impulsivity. Panel~C shows normalized wellbeing layer-sweep comparisons for Gemma~3 4B and Qwen~2.5 7B. Qwen yields the stronger probe (best $d = 3.544$) than Gemma (best $d = 1.815$).}}{32}{figure.caption.25}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:9}{{9}{32}{Supplementary scale and family analyses for Fig.~5. Panel~A shows probe quality across LLaMA 1B, 3B, and 8B, where each cell reports the maximum layer-wise Cohen's $d$. Probe quality varies strongly across both scale and concept, but all best-layer tests are significant in the expected direction ($p < 10^{-5}$). Panel~B shows mean logit self-report versus steering alpha for each concept and LLaMA size; shaded bands denote cluster-bootstrap 95\% CIs. Mixed-effects alpha slopes differ from zero in all twelve concept-size combinations, but the sign is inverted for 1B focus and 8B impulsivity. Panel~C shows normalized wellbeing layer-sweep comparisons for Gemma~3 4B and Qwen~2.5 7B. Qwen yields the stronger probe (best $d = 3.544$) than Gemma (best $d = 1.815$)}{figure.caption.25}{}}
